06567nam a22009495i 9789814951036DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20212020si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898149510367 a10.1355/97898149510362doi  a(DE-B1597)575769  a(OCoLC)1233041590  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 4aJQ750.A56C54bF76 2020 7aSOC0520002bisacsh04a959.05322300aFrom Grassroots Activism to Disinformation :bSocial Media in Southeast Asia /ced. by Aim Sinpeng, Ross Tapsell. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2021] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (234 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAbout the Contributors -- t1. From Grassroots Activism to Disinformation: Social Media Trends in Southeast Asia -- t2. Curing “Patient Zero”: Reclaiming the Digital Public Sphere in the Philippines -- t3. The Political Campaign Industry and the Rise of Disinformation in Indonesia -- t4. Disinformation as a Response to the “Opposition Playground” in Malaysia -- t5. Social Media, Hate Speech and Fake News during Myanmar’s Political Transition -- t6. Securitizing “Fake News”: Policy Responses to Disinformation in Thailand -- t7. Cambodia: From Democratization of Information to Disinformation -- t8. Social Media’s Challenge to State Information Controls in Vietnam -- t9. Social Media and Changes in Political Engagement in Singapore -- t10. Democratic Backsliding and Authoritarian Resilience in Southeast Asia: The Role of Social Media -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book reflects on the role of social media in the past two decades in Southeast Asia. It traces the emergence of social media discourse in Southeast Asia, and its potential as a “liberation technology” in both democratizing and authoritarian states. It explains the growing decline in internet freedom and increasingly repressive and manipulative use of social media tools by governments, and argues that social media is now an essential platform for control. The contributors detail the increasing role of “disinformation” and “fake news” production in Southeast Asia, and how national governments are creating laws which attempt to address this trend, but which often exacerbate the situation of state control. From Grassroots Activism to Disinformation explores three main questions: How did social media begin as a vibrant space for grassroots activism to becoming a tool for disinformation? Who were the main actors in this transition: governments, citizens or the platforms themselves? Can reformists “reclaim” the digital public sphere? And if so, how?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aCommunication in politicszSoutheast Asia. 0aCommunicationxPolitical aspectszSoutheast Asia. 0aDisinformationxPolitical aspectszSoutheast Asia. 0aSocial mediaxPolitical aspectszSoutheast Asia. 4aMedia Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh1 aBünte, Marco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheong, Niki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCombinido, Pamela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurato, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuong, Dien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNyi Kyaw, Nyi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPang, Natalie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSinpeng, Aim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSinpeng, Aim, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSombatpoonsiri, Janjira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular